ce:section.ce:para:
To verify the quenching process, the fluorescence lifetime decay of AC NCs in the absence and presence of DA were explored. In general, the fluorescence quenching divided into dynamic quenching and static quenching. In contrast, quenching caused by electron transfer of excited state is considered as a dynamic quenching process [30], and ground-state non-fluorescent complexes are formed between analyte and fluorescent probe as a static quenching process [1]. Furthermore, the fluorescence decay curves (Fig. 4
                        ) and the fluorescence lifetimes (Table 2
                        ) of the AC NCs were distinct in the absence and presence of DA, which means the DA-quenched AC NCs belong to the dynamic quenching [29].
